## An-Nisa

**An-Nisa** (The Women) is the fourth surah, **176 verses**, Medinan. It was revealed after the **Battle of Uhud**, where many Muslim men were killed. The community was left with widows, orphans, and estates that needed to be handled fairly.

That's the backdrop for everything in this surah. It's not abstract law. It's solving *real, urgent problems*.

---

## Orphans (1-6)

The surah opens with orphans, not women. Why? Because in pre-Islamic Arabia, when a man died, his male relatives would **seize everything**: his property, his wealth, sometimes even his widow. His children were left with nothing.

The Quran shuts this down:

> *"Give the orphans their property, and do not substitute your worthless things for their good ones, and do not consume their property by combining it with your own. This is truly a great sin."* (2)

Don't touch what belongs to orphans. Don't swap their valuable assets for your worthless ones. Don't mix their wealth with yours to quietly take from it.

The rules are specific: test orphans when they reach maturity, and if they show sound judgment, hand over their property. If they're not ready yet, manage it responsibly, but **don't consume it wastefully**.

