## Polygamy (3)

This verse is one of the most misunderstood in the Quran. It's directly connected to the orphan problem:

> *"If you fear you cannot deal justly with orphan girls, then marry other women of your choice, two or three or four. But if you fear you will not be just, then only one."* (3)

The context: after Uhud, many families lost their fathers. Guardians were now responsible for orphan girls and their inheritance. Some guardians wanted to marry these girls to gain their wealth *without* giving them a fair dowry.

The Quran says: if you can't be fair to orphan girls in your care, then marry *other* women instead. And even then, the limit is four, *with a strict condition*: you must treat them equally.

Later in the same surah:

> *"You will never be able to be perfectly just between wives, even if you try."* (129)

Many scholars read verses 3 and 129 together. The permission comes with a condition (perfect justice) that the Quran itself says is impossible. This is widely understood as **discouraging** polygamy, not encouraging it.

